        <h4 class="bento-sub">For agents where <span class="accent">review volume and reputation</span> drive the majority of new client inquiries.</h4>
        <p class="bento-desc">84% of buyers trust online reviews as much as personal referrals. Birdeye automates review requests after every closing and monitors your reputation across all platforms. For high-volume agents, reviews are the conversion layer that makes every other marketing investment pay off.</p>
        <div class="bento-cta">See full review <span class="arrow">↓</span></div>
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- METHODOLOGY -->
  <section class="problem-section">
    <div class="problem-header">
      <span class="label-pill">How we evaluated</span>
      <h2 class="h-lg">We scored <span class="accent">10 tools</span> on the five things that matter for real estate agent SEO.</h2>
      <p>We publish 30+ SEO articles per month for businesses across 70+ industries, including real estate agencies and solo agents. We've seen what moves rankings for realtors: consistent GBP activity, neighborhood-focused blog content, market report pages, review velocity, and clean directory listings on Realtor.com, Homes.com, and local MLS sites. We evaluated each tool against the five criteria that actually determine whether an agent gets found before their competitors.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="ba-grid">
      <div class="ba-col before">
        <div class="ba-head">
          <span class="ba-label">5 criteria we scored</span>
          <h3 class="ba-title">What real estate agents actually need from SEO tools.</h3>
          <p class="ba-sub">Same scorecard across all 10 tools.</p>
        </div>
        <ul class="ba-list">
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">01</span>
            <div>
              <h4>GBP Management</h4>
              <p>"Realtor near me" and "real estate agent [city]" searches pull from GBP. Motivated sellers and relocating buyers start here. If your profile isn't active, you're invisible.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">02</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Content Creation</h4>
              <p>Neighborhood pages, market reports, and buying guides rank for hundreds of hyperlocal searches Zillow will never target. This is the content lane only local agents can own.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">03</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Review Management</h4>
              <p>84% of buyers trust online reviews as much as personal referrals. Reviews directly impact local pack ranking and close-rate from inquiry to first meeting.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">04</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Local Rank Tracking</h4>
              <p>You need to know if "homes for sale [neighborhood]" is moving up or down — and across every neighborhood you serve, not just your primary market.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">05</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Citation Management</h4>
              <p>Realtor.com, Homes.com, Zillow agent profiles, and 90+ directories need consistent NAP data. Inconsistent listings hurt your local pack ranking.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="ba-col after">
        <div class="ba-head">
          <span class="ba-label">What we found</span>
          <h3 class="ba-title">The content gap between busy agents and ranking agents is enormous.</h3>
          <p class="ba-sub">Three findings from our evaluation.</p>
        </div>
        <ul class="ba-list">
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">01</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Most agents have a 5-page website — the top-ranking agent has 360+ content pages</h4>
              <p>The average solo agent has a website with listing pages, an About Me, and a contact form. The agent ranking #1 for "moving to [city]" has published 360+ articles about neighborhoods, schools, market data, and local life.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">02</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Zillow owns listing searches — neighborhood content is the only lane agents can win</h4>
              <p>"Homes for sale in Dallas" belongs to Zillow. "Best neighborhoods in Dallas for young professionals" belongs to whoever writes it first. That content doesn't exist on Zillow.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">03</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Automation is the only path to publishing consistency for active agents</h4>
