        </div>
        <p style="color: var(--text-2); margin: 0 0 20px;">Real estate agents know they should be blogging. The National Association of Realtors says 97% of buyers use the internet during their home search. But between showings, closings, open houses, and client calls, who has time to write about "best neighborhoods in Austin for first-time buyers"? Nobody. That's who. The result: a website with 5 listing pages and an About Me that hasn't been updated since you got your license. Meanwhile, the agent ranking #1 for "moving to [your city]" publishes 3–4 blog posts per week. theStacc closes that gap. It publishes 30 neighborhood-focused articles per month directly to your website: "best neighborhoods in [city] for families," "[city] housing market forecast 2026," "cost of living in [neighborhood]." The Local SEO module adds 30 GBP posts per month — market updates, open house announcements, neighborhood highlights — without you writing a word.</p>
        <ul class="ba-list">
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">✓</span>
            <div>
              <h4>30 real estate articles/month — neighborhood guides, market reports, relocation content</h4>
              <p>Topics Zillow will never create: hyperlocal content that positions you as the neighborhood expert before a prospect ever picks up the phone. 30 articles = 360 new Google entry points per year.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">✓</span>
            <div>
              <h4>30 GBP posts/month — market updates, just-sold announcements, neighborhood spotlights</h4>
              <p>Daily GBP activity signals relevance to Google's local algorithm. While competing agents post once a month (if that), your profile publishes automatically every day.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">✓</span>
            <div>
              <h4>~$126/month bundled — less than one print ad, 60 pieces of content per month</h4>
              <p>A freelance real estate writer charges $2,400–7,500/month for 30 articles. A real estate marketing agency charges $1,500–5,000/month. theStacc delivers 30 articles + 30 GBP posts for ~$126/month.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">✗</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Honest con: no IDX integration, no MLS feed, no review management</h4>
              <p>theStacc creates blog content and GBP posts — it doesn't pull listing data or manage your online reputation. You'll need BrightLocal for rank tracking and Birdeye for reviews alongside it.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <div style="margin-top: 24px;">
          <a href="/checkout/" class="btn btn-primary"><span>Start the $1 trial <span class="arrow">→</span></span></a>
          <a href="/modules/content-seo/" class="btn btn-secondary" style="margin-left: 12px;">See Content SEO module</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- TOOL 2 -->
    <div class="ba-grid" id="tool-2" style="margin-top: 48px;">
      <div class="ba-col before" style="grid-column: 1 / -1;">
        <div class="ba-head">
          <span class="ba-label">#2 · FREE · FOUNDATION TOOL</span>
          <h3 class="ba-title">Google Business Profile — Best free foundation for real estate agent SEO</h3>
          <p class="ba-sub">Not optional. Every agent needs a fully optimized GBP before spending on any paid tool.</p>
        </div>
        <p style="color: var(--text-2); margin: 0 0 20px;">Google Business Profile controls your appearance in the local 3-pack — the map results above organic listings. For real estate agents, this is where motivated sellers and relocating buyers start their search. A complete GBP with accurate info, photos, and regular posts outranks an incomplete profile every time. Here's the move most agents miss: add every neighborhood you serve as a service area. If you serve 12 neighborhoods, list all 12. An agent who lists "Buckhead, Midtown, Virginia-Highland, Decatur" in their service areas ranks for more location-specific searches than one who lists only "Atlanta."</p>
        <ul class="ba-list">
          <li><span class="ba-num">✓</span><div><h4>Free — the most important SEO action any agent can take at zero cost</h4><p>Claim, verify, and complete your profile before spending a dollar on paid tools. This is the foundation everything else builds on.</p></div></li>
          <li><span class="ba-num">✓</span><div><h4>Service area configuration — add every neighborhood you serve to rank for more searches</h4><p>List every neighborhood and zip code you cover. Google uses service areas to determine relevance for location-specific searches.</p></div></li>
          <li><span class="ba-num">✓</span><div><h4>Real photos drive trust — properties you've sold, headshots, your team</h4><p>Not stock photos. Real estate is a relationship business. Photos of you, your team, and your sold properties build immediate trust.</p></div></li>
          <li><span class="ba-num">✗</span><div><h4>Honest con: manual everything — your GBP goes silent when you're closing deals</h4><p>During your busiest selling seasons, your GBP will stop getting updates unless you automate. Pair with theStacc Local SEO module to keep posting automatically.</p></div></li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- TOOL 3 -->
    <div class="ba-grid" id="tool-3" style="margin-top: 48px;">
      <div class="ba-col before" style="grid-column: 1 / -1;">
        <div class="ba-head">
          <span class="ba-label">#3 · $39–59/MO · MONTHLY CONTRACT</span>
          <h3 class="ba-title">BrightLocal — Best local rank tracking for real estate agents</h3>
          <p class="ba-sub">For agents who need to know exactly where they rank for every real estate keyword across every neighborhood they serve.</p>
        </div>
        <p style="color: var(--text-2); margin: 0 0 20px;">Real estate is hyperlocal. Ranking #3 for "realtor in Buckhead" and #27 for "realtor in Midtown" tells you exactly where to focus. BrightLocal's Local Search Grid shows your ranking position on a map — green means you're visible, red means you're invisible. For agents covering a metro area with 15+ neighborhoods, this visual map reveals exactly where your SEO is working and where it's not. The citation tracker monitors your listings on Realtor.com, Homes.com, Zillow's agent directory, and 80+ other platforms to ensure your contact info is consistent everywhere.</p>
        <ul class="ba-list">
          <li><span class="ba-num">✓</span><div><h4>Local Search Grid — see your ranking position across every neighborhood you serve</h4><p>Visual map of ranking positions across your service area. When you can see you rank #2 in one zip and #18 in the next, you know exactly where to invest content effort.</p></div></li>
          <li><span class="ba-num">✓</span><div><h4>GBP audit — identifies every gap in your real estate agent profile</h4><p>Flags missing service areas, incomplete descriptions, and photo opportunities specific to your profile. Particularly useful for agents who haven't touched their GBP since they got their license.</p></div></li>
          <li><span class="ba-num">✓</span><div><h4>Citation tracking across real estate directories — Realtor.com, Homes.com, Zillow agent profile</h4><p>Inconsistent NAP data across directories hurts local pack ranking. BrightLocal catches inconsistencies before they compound.</p></div></li>
          <li><span class="ba-num">✗</span><div><h4>Honest con: BrightLocal tracks what theStacc builds — pair them, don't choose one</h4><p>BrightLocal shows you the rank gap. theStacc creates the neighborhood content that closes it. They're complementary tools, not alternatives.</p></div></li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- TOOL 4 -->
    <div class="ba-grid" id="tool-4" style="margin-top: 48px;">
